 it is working at all. The second issue is causal: what are the claims being made regarding how best to secure a democratic system in developing states? To what extent do our beliefs and expectations of how political relations ought to be governed distort our understanding of how democratic societies do in fact emerge; and, conversely, to what extent does our understanding of how democracy manifests itself temper our conception of what it ought to be?The volume will be of interest to those in international development studies, as well as political theorists with an interest in applied ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aDemocracy. 0aWorld politicsx1989-. 0aWorld politicsy1989-. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  acivil society.  acomparative development.  ademocratic norms.  ademocratic system.  ademocratic theory.  ademocratization debates.  adeveloping states.  aeconomic well-being.  aglobalization of democracy.  alegitimacy.  aphilosophical ideals.  apolitical obstacles.  apolitical strategy.  arobust democracy.1 aFierlbeck, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779431440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794314/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles